  "text": "Despite the potential anti-predator benefits that could be associated with adopting TI behaviours (discussed above), there are also likely to be related costs. Some of these costs will impact evolutionary trade-offs in species, influencing variation in TI expression and its prevalence. Alternative last-ditch anti-predator behaviours, such as struggling to break free and fleeing or aggressively attacking the would-be predator, will also probably have benefits and costs that will influence their expression. Hence, we might expect the prevalence and strength of TI to reflect conditions where the cost-benefit trade-off favours TI over alternative behavioural tactics. As an example of this, [CITATION_1] found that TI in larvae of the damselfly Ischnura elegans was more likely to be utilised in staged laboratory encounters with predators if an alternate anti-predator defence was negated by removal of lamellae; otherwise, lamellae can be sacrificed through autotomy, as an escape strategy, when grasped by a predator.",
